cisions. Working at the intersection of literature, international law, and globalized commerce, Goodman astutely pinpoints how policing has become an increasingly troublesome instrument of empire, particularly in terms of national sovereignty and the growing numbers of mercenary private security forces.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aDetective and mystery stories, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aDetective and mystery stories, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aLaw enforcement in literature. 0aLaw enforcementxPolitical aspects. 0aPolice in literature. 0aPolicezUnited StatesxBiographyxHistory and criticism. 0aSovereignty in literature. 0aState, The, in literature. 0aWar on Terrorism, 2001-2009xPolitical aspects. 4aBusiness and Economics : Business and Government. 4aBusiness and Economics : International Business. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Economy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Mystery & Detective.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143842905240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438429052423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438429052/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles